VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of the uh perks of having Gaussian splatting is this view dependence effects, this uh behaving great with uh reflective surfaces. How does the plugin manages and deals with this, let\'s say, more'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complex, in a way, uh surfaces? &gt;&gt; Right. So, there are two ways and we like to see the plugin as an hybrid approach, where we can you can combine Gaussian splats and traditional'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'graphics. So, Gaussian splats are probably or as you know, but it\'s good to refresh, are really good at representing reflective surfaces or surfaces that change depending on the view direction, and'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s because it besides the base color, it has or they have the spherical harmonics. This is not not our thing, but let\'s say a mapping that tells you, "Hey, if you are looking me from this'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction, this is the color, and if you are looking me from this other direction, this is the color." So, uh the spherical harmonics have different levels. Mean, this means the higher the level of your spherical'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'harmonics, the more computation you will need, but the more complex reflections you can model. Our plugin use until the third level, which is probably the highest that you have out there.'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh And yeah, that lives very well with with with the plugin Unreal. But, this is important to have in mind that this is not actually a physical material. This are this are trick, let\'s say, to'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'represent these reflections. And for instance, it could happen of having a reflective surfaces and a splat reflecting something that is in front of the splat, and it looks very realistic, but in the moment you add a 3D element'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into the scene, it won\'t reflect on on that surface, because this is not a metallic material. It\'s just uh let\'s say the splats are learning, they have the reflections, but they are not understanding it.'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh so, that\'s the part where we are added something we call proximus behavior, where we allow the user to introduce a proxy geometry, uh'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s say, make that geometry and that mesh share some properties with the splat. And one of them are the materials. So, in that way, you are telling our plugin, "Hey, this section of the splat Uh,'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have the specific materials and that\'s where, okay, we saw giving this plots or giving our plugin this understanding of how the material behaves uh, instead of just, you know, representing what it was captured.'

[07:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, is this because when doing some research, I\'ve seen that you describe this relating approach in two ways, like additive lighting and mesh-based lighting. Is that part of this distinction? Can you maybe uh, break'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those down for us? And when do they apply also to the concept of the reflectiveness and adding this mesh-based with certain properties? Sure. So, the main difference between uh, so there are two different concepts'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we will call to additive lighting or we say mesh-based uh, lighting. So, the additive lighting we call this in the or we refer to that to the way we relight on the plugin.'

[08:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh, why is that? Actually, when you capture a Gaussian splat, you already capturing the light of the of the which in certain occasions that\'s what you want and it\'s great and this looks really realistic especially on uh, you know, when you have like a'

[08:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh, skyfall or you know, so there is a lot of uh, situation where you would like this uh, to happen. But there are lots where you just need to change the light conditions of this splat. The problem is'

[08:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that if you capture this splat and you have shadows on it and you have some light behavior, you are not removing the light. That\'s why we\'re calling this additive lighting because you are just adding on top of what you have. Uh,'

[09:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there are some companies like people where are doing a really good job of doing this the lighting and removing everything and just, you know, getting the the composition of albedo uh, the rest of the materials.'

[09:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Which there\'s some experimental workflows in which you can combine people with Gaussian splats to remove the existing light and then in that moment, let\'s say you do that with a plugin that will be'

[09:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually a lighting without additive lighting because you have removed. But when we say additive lighting, it\'s hey, we are just adding on top of what you\'re giving us. And because we are assuming you\'re not giving us a clean albedo. It\'s something'

[09:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what you capture. And then difference between mesh based lighting and additive lighting is that well, and the rest of the lighting is that in general on the plugin, we estimate the normals and that\'s all because we we cannot estimate at this'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'moment the properties of the materials. However, as I explained before, if you use the Proxima\'s uh part of our plugin, you can provide the normal the normals but also the properties of the materials. And that\'s'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we will call next mesh based lighting. So we are not estimating the normals. Let\'s say the user is giving them to us. &gt;&gt; So I want to go back on one thing just so that I understood correctly. Are you saying basically there are some teams'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right now that are doing delighting of Gaussian splatting? So there is some research that allows to let\'s say remove harsh shadow potentially or some of this? Is is that correct? &gt;&gt; That\'s the idea. Yes, and with some work'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that is let\'s say it\'s a smart approach because it\'s not doing uh the delighting on the Gaussian splatting. It\'s doing the delighting before the Gaussian splatting is is generated. So on the data set on the'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'images, the soft images. So what these teams are doing is using two technologies like Bebo AI uh to remove the the harsh shadows and all the light uh of the Gaussian splats. And'

